full_content:
Article 89
(1) The Minister or appointed Immigration Official carries out preventive and repressive efforts in order to prevent criminal acts of human trafficking and human smuggling.
(2) Preventive efforts as intended in paragraph (1) are carried out by:
a. exchange of information with other countries and relevant domestic agencies, including modus operandi, supervision and security of Travel Documents, as well as legitimacy and validity of documents;
b. technical cooperation and training with other countries including humanitarian treatment of victims, security and quality of Travel Documents, detection of fake documents, exchange of information, as well as monitoring and detection of Human Smuggling using conventional and non-conventional methods;
c. provide legal education to the public that human trafficking and human smuggling are criminal acts so that people do not become victims;
d. guarantee that the Travel Document or identity issued is of good quality so that the document is not easily misused, counterfeited, altered, imitated, or issued unlawfully; and
e. ensure that the integrity and security of Travel Documents issued or published by or on behalf of the state to prevent the creation of these documents unlawfully in terms of their issuance and use.
(3) Repressive efforts as intended in paragraph (1) are carried out by:
a. Immigration investigations into perpetrators of criminal acts of human trafficking and human smuggling;
b. Immigration Administrative Action against perpetrators of criminal acts of human trafficking and Human Smuggling; and
c. cooperation in the field of investigations with other law enforcement agencies.

